    <title>A Proof and a Way to Get PI</title>
    <url>/2020/10/30/A-Proof-and-a-Way-to-Get-PI/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<h1 id="Euler-Poisson-Intergal-and-Wallis-Formula"><a href="#Euler-Poisson-Intergal-and-Wallis-Formula" class="headerlink" title="Euler-Poisson Intergal and Wallis Formula"></a>Euler-Poisson Intergal and Wallis Formula</h1><blockquote>
<p>This passage  comes from Euler-Poisson Integral:</p>
</blockquote>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\int_{0}^{+\infty} \mathrm{e}^{-x^{2}}\mathrm{d}x =\frac{\sqrt{\pi}}{2}</script><h2 id="An-analysis-question"><a href="#An-analysis-question" class="headerlink" title="An analysis question"></a>An analysis question</h2><p>Let</p>
<p> $f(x)=\int_{0}^{1} \frac{e^{-x^{2}(y^{2}+1)}}{y^2+1}\mathrm{d}x$, and $g(x)=(\int_{0}^{x}\mathrm{e}^{-y^{2}}\mathrm{d}y)^{2}$, and $f+g=\frac{\pi}{4}$,(with derivation we can find $f+g$ is a constant function), we can proof the Euler-Poisson Integral.</p>
<p>And this is the first meet between me and E-P Integral.</p>
<h2 id="Solve-the-Integral-Directly"><a href="#Solve-the-Integral-Directly" class="headerlink" title="Solve the Integral Directly?"></a>Solve the Integral Directly?</h2><p>From the book of Demidovich, I saw a question below:</p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\text{Use the Transposition of integral and limit operations to solve it}</script><script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\int_{0}^{+\infty} \mathrm{e}^{-x^{2}}\mathrm{d}x=\int_{0}^{+\infty} \lim_{n \to \infty}\left [ \left( 1+ \frac{x^{2}}{n}\right)^{-n}\right ]\mathrm{d}x</script><p>So we can have a try:</p>
<p>Easy to judge that the function under the limit operation is continuous and uniform convergence, so we can safely exchange the order of two operations.</p>
<p>That comes a big problem, <strong>HOW TO CALCULATE THE INGERAL INSIDE</strong>?</p>
<p>That is why I write.</p>
<p>We write it outside of the limit. What I need to deal with is:</p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{\mathrm{d}x}{\left (1 +\frac{x^2}{n} \right )^{n}}</script><p>Use $t$ to replace $x$, $t=\frac{x}{\sqrt{n}}$, the integral comes to:</p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\sqrt{n}\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{\mathrm{d}t}{(1+t^{2})^{n}}</script><p>Then we create a function sequence $I_{n}$, and let the $(5) = \sqrt{n}I_{n}$.</p>
<p>Thus we need to deal with the sequence. We can try <strong>integration by parts</strong> to find the relations between $I_{n} \&amp; I_{n-1}   $.</p>
<p>Luckily,</p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
I_{n-1} = \left.\frac{t}{(1+t^{2})^{n-1}}\right|_{0} ^{+\infty} + 2(n-1)\int_{0}^{+\infty}\frac{t^{2}}{(1+t^{2})^{n}}\mathrm{d}x</script><p>We find the former is equal to 0, and the latter can be written as $2(n-1)I_{n-1}-2(n-1)I_{n}$</p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
I_{n} = \frac{2n-3}{2n-2}I_{n-1}</script><p>Just to calculate $I_{1}$ and everything is solved.</p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
I_{n}=\frac{(2n -3)!!}{(2n-2)!!}\cdot \frac{\pi}{2}</script><p>While after we bring back the $I_{n}$ to the Integral, </p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\int_{0}^{+\infty}\mathrm{e}^{-x^{2}}\mathrm{d}x = \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{(2n -3)!!}{(2n-2)!!}\frac{\pi \sqrt{n}}{2}</script><p>something strange happened, maybe we have to do something with $\frac{\pi}{2}$?</p>
<h2 id="Wallis-Formula"><a href="#Wallis-Formula" class="headerlink" title="Wallis Formula"></a>Wallis Formula</h2><blockquote>
<p>The Wallis Formula is here, the as</p>
</blockquote>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\lim _{n \rightarrow+\infty}\left(\frac{(2 n) ! !}{(2 n-1) ! !}\right)^{2} \frac{1}{2 n+1}=\frac{\pi}{2}</script><p>It comes from the integral </p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
S_{n}=\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}}\sin^{n}{x}\mathrm{d}x</script><p>Yes, this can use the same way to solve, we can get a relation between $S_{n} \&amp; S_{n-2} $, </p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
I_{n}=\frac{n-1}{n} I_{n-2}</script><p>With the monotonicity of $\sin^{n}x$, we have a unequal relationship:</p>
<script type="math/tex; mode=display">
\frac{2 k ! !}{(2 k+1) ! !}<\frac{(2 k-1) ! !}{2 k ! !} \frac{\pi}{2}<\frac{(2 k-2) ! !}{(2 k-1) ! !}</script><p>Let $n \to \infty$ so the Wallis Formula is proofed.</p>
<p>Until now, the question of Euler-Possion Integral is finish.</p>
]]></content>
