    <title>Quotients</title>
    <url>/2020/10/16/Abstruct-algebra/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<h1 id="quotient">Quotient</h1>
<blockquote>
<p>Too much to learn</p>
</blockquote>
<h2 id="quotient-define-examples">Quotient Define &amp; Examples</h2>
<p>In the algebra, many system has its quotient system, like <code>quotient group</code>,<code>quotient set</code>, and so on.</p>
<p>### Quotient Group</p>
<p>The quotient needs to define a relation just like <span class="math inline">\(R\)</span>, to simplify the argument, I use group to discuss.</p>
<p>with the defined relationship, we have a <code>Left Coset</code> , the Left Cosets build up the <code>quotient group</code>, we can present each elements by the Representative of equivalence class, we write them as <span class="math inline">\(\bar a, \bar b \dots\)</span></p>
<p><span class="math inline">\(\bar a\)</span> Represent each elements that equal to <span class="math inline">\(a\)</span> under the relationship <span class="math inline">\({R}\)</span></p>
<p>the simplest example is the set <span class="math inline">\(\mathbb{Z}\)</span> under the calculate <code>+</code>, and <span class="math inline">\(\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z}\)</span>, the quotient group of it.</p>
<p>the elements in $/m $, just like <span class="math inline">\(\bar 1, \bar 2, \cdots, \overline{m-1}\)</span>, in the <code>+</code>, the equation is presented as $  a - b = i$, so $a &amp; b $ is in the set <span class="math inline">\(\overline{i}\)</span>, in the <span class="math inline">\(\times\)</span> is the <span class="math inline">\(ab^{-1} \in \overline{i}\)</span>.</p>
]]></content>
