    <title>Sylow Theorems</title>
    <url>/2020/10/24/sylow-theorems/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<h1 id="sylow-theorems">Sylow Theorems</h1>
<blockquote>
<p>Too much to learn</p>
</blockquote>
<h2 id="lemmas-for-sylow-theorems">Lemmas for Sylow Theorems</h2>
<p><strong>Define 1 <em>p-Group</em></strong> Let <span class="math inline">\(p\)</span> a prime number, if the <code>order</code> of Group <code>G</code> is <span class="math inline">\(p^{k}, k&gt; 0\)</span>, then we called <code>G</code> <span class="math inline">\(p-group\)</span>.</p>
<p>All we discussion is based on the <span class="math inline">\(p-group\)</span>.</p>
<p><strong>Lemma 1</strong> Let a <span class="math inline">\(p-group\)</span> acting on set <span class="math inline">\(X\)</span>, the order of <span class="math inline">\(X\)</span> equals to <span class="math inline">\(n\)</span>, which written as <span class="math inline">\(|X| = n\)</span>, we have result listed below:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><span class="math inline">\(t \equiv n\mod p\)</span>, in the equation, <span class="math inline">\(t = \left |\{x | x \in X, g(x) = x, \forall g\in G\}\right|\)</span>;</li>
<li>When <span class="math inline">\((n,p) = 1\)</span>, then <span class="math inline">\(t \geq 1\)</span>, and there are some Fixed points in <span class="math inline">\(X\)</span>;</li>
<li>The center of <code>G</code> <span class="math inline">\(C(G) \neq \lbrace e \rbrace\)</span>.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>proof</strong></p>
]]></content>
